TY  - JOUR
TI  - Coagulopathy after isolated traumatic brain injury: a prospective cohort study
AU  - Smith, John A.
AU  - Jones, Mary B.
T2  - Journal of Neurotrauma
PY  - 2021
VL  - 38
IS  - 4
AB  - Background: Coagulopathy is a recognised complication following traumatic brain injury (TBI). This prospective cohort study examined coagulation markers in 120 adult patients with isolated TBI admitted to a level-1 trauma centre. Methods: PT, PTT, INR, fibrinogen, and platelet counts were measured at admission and 24 hours post-injury. Results: 43% of patients developed coagulopathy within 24 hours. Severity correlated with GCS on admission. Conclusions: Isolated TBI frequently induces coagulopathy; early monitoring is warranted.
DO  - 10.1089/neu.2020.7412
KW  - traumatic brain injury; coagulopathy; PT; INR; fibrinogen
LA  - English
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Effect of tranexamic acid on outcomes in traumatic brain injury: a randomised trial
AU  - Williams, Claire D.
AU  - Brown, Peter R.
T2  - The Lancet
PY  - 2022
VL  - 399
IS  - 10321
AB  - This randomised controlled trial assessed whether tranexamic acid administered within 3 hours of isolated TBI reduced mortality and coagulopathy-related complications in 500 adult patients. The intervention group received 1g IV TXA; the control group received placebo. Primary outcome was 28-day mortality. Secondary outcomes included coagulopathy markers. No significant difference in mortality was observed; however, the TXA group showed improved coagulation profiles at 6 hours post-injury.
DO  - 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)00001-1
KW  - tranexamic acid; TBI; RCT; coagulopathy; mortality
LA  - English
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
TI  - A review of haemostatic dysfunction in neurotrauma
AU  - Garcia, Luis M.
T2  - Neurocritical Care
PY  - 2020
VL  - 33
IS  - 2
AB  - This narrative review summarises the current literature on haemostatic dysfunction following neurotrauma, including traumatic brain injury and spinal cord injury. Mechanisms of coagulopathy, including disseminated intravascular coagulation, hyperfibrinolysis, and platelet dysfunction, are discussed. Treatment strategies are reviewed. No new primary data are presented.
DO  - 10.1007/s12028-020-00934-4
KW  - review; neurotrauma; haemostasis; coagulopathy; DIC
LA  - English
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Prevalence of diabetes mellitus in urban populations of sub-Saharan Africa
AU  - Okonkwo, Adaeze N.
AU  - Mensah, Kwame O.
T2  - Diabetes Research and Clinical Practice
PY  - 2021
VL  - 175
IS  - 1
AB  - This cross-sectional survey investigated the prevalence of type 2 diabetes mellitus across five urban centres in sub-Saharan Africa. A total of 8,400 adults aged 25-65 were screened. Prevalence ranged from 6.2% to 11.8% across sites. Obesity and physical inactivity were the strongest risk factors. No data on traumatic brain injury or coagulation were collected.
DO  - 10.1016/j.diabres.2021.108785
KW  - diabetes; Africa; epidemiology; prevalence
LA  - English
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Platelet dysfunction in polytrauma patients with and without TBI
AU  - Chen, Wei L.
AU  - Nakamura, Hiro T.
T2  - Injury
PY  - 2023
VL  - 54
IS  - 3
AB  - We retrospectively analysed platelet function in 340 polytrauma patients admitted to our trauma centre, comparing those with TBI to those without. Platelet aggregation was significantly impaired in TBI patients. However, all patients had at least one additional major injury (ISS ≥16 excluding TBI). This study does not isolate the effect of TBI alone.
DO  - 10.1016/j.injury.2022.11.019
KW  - polytrauma; platelet; TBI; coagulopathy
LA  - English
ER  -

